# **Athena \- Revised Onboarding Details**

---

# **Key Points**

*General themes for improving onboarding*

* Condense time period of playbook implementation  
  * Require *at least* the following prior to kickoff call  
    * 1Password share of main work/personal Gmail accounts with EA  
    * Client-defined delegation stack (particularly task management platform for EA)  
  * Execute all foundation playbooks during kickoff call on screenshare using simplified templates  
    * Prefill by AI or [manually by EA](#pre-ai/pre-productization-implementations); make ‚Äúpush‚Äù rather than ‚Äúpull‚Äù  
* Consolidate documents wherever possible  
  * Repurpose original [Preferences Google Sheet](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/13VbmOxH_2qOmDPpxC-DP4b7_l2oV_eUROHgc95oDdQs/preview) with 13 tabs into similar formats, e.g.  
    * vs [single document version](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1nTo0Vhazd27EnwM5V87WDFRSO9t-YyxIonZ-hlAl3LI/preview)  
    * vs [simplified multi-tab version](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1PJ5OYeta1IX5uwSnNpHdrKAeABHYncNEScMYf2Tp5_8/preview) (likely preferred)  
    * vs [simplified single-tab version](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/14zkcUIz2leYPNWAWr9tgPqN3zLUYoMqawLiVFB5xNQM/preview)  
  * Avoid distributing content in separate places   
    * I.e. web portal vs Google Doc template vs Notion template, etc  
  * Prefill documents with AI or [manually by EA](#pre-ai/pre-productization-implementations) and dedicate KOC to making minor edits live  
    * Using above templates or separate docs, as with [AI-Extracted Hotel Preferences & Booking SOP](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1y9o44JCFZrDqQkYSrbfmw83zdtUtlFfCc9xYS5rcuZs/edit?usp=sharing)  
* Use a mutual action plan approach rather than internal website for client-facing actions  
  * Either in Google Sheets ([template](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1hRDK6cBgTkIO9hR4QKB2ZAban_mYbQrEdgz3U4KIkAY/edit?gid=0#gid=0)) or assign client/EA tasks via project manager like ClickUp  
  * Gate onboarding progress by client actions (e.g. match, kickoff call)  
* Run check-ins more like executive coaching call format  
  * I.e. set goals and schedule/assign actions, elicit delegation ideas with questions, review performance from last call  
* Augment call scripts and related content with personalized AI suggestions, when able  
  * Pull data from APIs from waitlist form email address \+ enrichment SaaS, require Google auth prior to Discovery Call to extract data from email, etc

# **Call Outlines**

For each call, we‚Äôve aimed to rework the format to enable clients to experience value earlier, implement churn-reducing systems, and better empower EAs to deliver outcomes.

## **2-Way Fit Call**

*Suggested high-level format for discovery call; likely least important to revise*

* Goals  
  * Qualify the client and assess potential churn risk  
  * Convey the value and benefits of Athena's EA service  
  * Inspire the client with specific (ideally personalized) examples and anecdotes  
  * Address potential concerns and objections, if any  
  * Ensure client understands the long-term nature of the EA relationship  
* Pre-Call Actions  
  * Review lead enrichment data (e.g., Apollo)  
  * Prepare relevant anecdotes and delegation examples based on client's profile, or review AI suggestions thereof  
  * Review any potential churn risk factors based on client data  
* Mid-Call Actions  
  * Review relevant delegations on screenshare  
  * Assess client risks (e.g. previous EA issues, funding situation, expectation misalignment, impatience, etc)  
* Post-Call Actions  
  * Ideally follow up with personalized suggestions, links, or delegations  
  * Communicate (potential) rejection, if necessary  
  * Assign client tasks prior to discovery call  
    * Recommend these are optional and simply used to surreptitiously assess client engagement level


## **Discovery Call**

*Suggested high-level format for discovery call*

* Goals  
  * Identify specific, actionable delegation opportunities  
  * Establish clear client goals and milestones for the EA partnership  
  * Understand client's decision-making preferences and collaboration style  
  * Create a tailored onboarding journey and user manual focused on EA effectiveness  
  * Set realistic expectations for the partnership's evolution  
* Pre-Call Actions  
  * AI  
    * Generate client profile & suggested delegations (more accurate when able to use extensive social media presence or podcasts)  
  * OBM  
    * Review AI/API-based client profile & suggestions  
* Mid-Call Actions  
  * OBM  
    * Long-Term Goal Setting  
      * What leverage we want in W1 & W2 vs M1 & M2 vs M6 and M12  
      * Superordinate vs intermediate vs subordinate goals  
        * Personally & professionally:  
          * Where do we want to be in 2-5 years?  
          * What are we doing now or what do we plan to do to make that happen?  
          * What parts of that can we delegate?  
    * Determine key EA skills   
      * E.g. travel, verbal communication, automation, etc  
    * Establish [focus areas](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JvVlSOi1x5Hjn4-RPeWWGvZGrOv6ywo9otjHeWDGAGc/edit#heading=h.pneypgke88po) & playbook choices for short- vs. medium-term (beyond foundations)  
* Post-Call Actions  
  * AI  
    * Generate match factors & ideal EA profile  
    * Generate user manual & extract foundation preferences  
      * Future: generate AI SOPs  
  * OBM  
    * Review/edit AI-generated docs and send to client  
  * Client  
    * Complete SaaS stack doc/sheet  
    * Set up 1Password and share main personal/work email \+ calendar \+ docs account with dummy email (e.g. [clientname@athena.com](mailto:clientname@athena.com), later aliased to EA‚Äôs Athena email)  
    * Review user manual & SOPs  
* Reference Artifacts  
  * [User Manual](#consolidated-ai-user-manual-&-sops) & [AI SOPs](#consolidated-ai-user-manual-&-sops)  
  * [Journey Docs/Visuals](#mock-1-2y-journey-spreadsheet-&-timeline)  
  * [EA Norms & Collaboration Nuances](#ea-norms-&-collaboration-nuances)

## **Kickoff Call**

*Suggested high-level format for kickoff call*

* Goals  
  * Experience quick wins  
  * Implement key systems, e.g. email/calendar  
  * Develop long-term goals and vision  
  * Practice core delegation skills  
  * Set specific 1-week, 1-month, and other milestones  
* Pre-Call Actions  
  * Client  
    * Create 1Password account and share personal \+ work inbox/calendar accounts  
    * Complete preferences document(s), e.g. tool stack  
  * EA  
    * Review user manual \+ SOPs \+ other content  
    * Create task management workspace for client (e.g. ClickUp, Asana, etc)  
    * Open client email, calendar, docs, and task management workspace  
    * Edit initial proactive value-add items   
      * E.g., check and edit gift recipient spreadsheet, create ideal week calendar (new calendar in client account), create email labels, etc  
        * These must all be reversible, but we should ask for permission or provide a notice to client before the call  
  * OBM  
    * Open slide deck with example inspiring delegations, exercises, etc  
    * Edit AI-generated delegation suggestions from client email/calendar  
      * E.g. as Google Doc or Sheet blending generally recommended delegations (recurring appointments, etc) and personalized client recommendations from AI  
  * AI  
    * Create draft user manual  
      * Revised format for greater EA usability  
    * Create draft SOPs  
      * Calendar  
      * Email  
      * Travel  
        * Flights  
        * Hotels & Airbnb  
      * Other  
    * Suggest playbooks for recurring delegations  
    * Suggest quick win delegations from similar users  
    * Generate client email style guide and prompt with few shot examples  
    * Generate edited version of client onboarding slide deck from template  
* Mid-Call Actions  
  * Client  
    * Answer simple questions enabling the configuration of foundation playbooks by EA during the call  
      * ‚ÄúDoes this recommended Athena email labeling & delegation system look good?‚Äù ‚Üí ‚ÄúYes‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúDoes this AI-generated SOP for your flight preferences look good, or do we need to edit any data points?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the earliest and latest time you‚Äôd like for meetings?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúMost clients like to batch certain kinds of meetings on certain days of the week. How would you like to do it?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúFor sales follow-up emails, do you prefer EA to pre-draft as themselves, or as you?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúThis is what we found for gifts, does it look right to you?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúIt looks like you‚Äôve gotten massages at X. How often would we like \[EA\] to schedule these for you? Should they verify over email or Slack first, or just make an appointment and cancel if need be?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs review your email style guide and a few example output emails that \[EA\] wrote with ChatGPT. Do these look good, or how can we tweak the prompt?‚Äù  
    * Review suggested quick win delegations & recurring delegations  
      * Delegate 1 ad hoc and 1 recurring delegation on the call  
    * Practice delegations, including both text and voice  
    * Practice giving feedback  
      * Can involve a hypothetical situation, after reviewing examples of good vs bad delegation feedback in slide deck with OBM  
  * EA  
    * Implement playbooks in real-time based on client preferences  
      * Create email labels  
      * Edit Google Docs for SOPs  
      * Create tasks in project manager  
      * Schedule meetings  
    * Identify potential quick wins and near-term needs via sweep  
      * ‚ÄúDo you have any trips coming up?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúAre there any birthday, mother‚Äôs/father‚Äôs day, anniversary, or other gift events coming up?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúAre we overdue for any medical stuff, like lab tests or specialist visits?‚Äù  
      * ‚ÄúAre we in need of a massage, spa day, outdoors trip, date night, or help with another occasion?‚Äù  
    * Fill out doc/sheet/slides of where we want to be in 1, 2, 4, 12, 52 weeks  
  * OBM  
    * Elicit client preferences on SOPs and EA collaboration  
    * Guide client practice delegations  
    * Collaboratively set delegation goals  
  * AI  
    * Generate transcript & summary (later, split action items & assign via API)  
* Post-Call Actions  
  * EA  
    * Move any approved delegations to project manager  
    * Update mutual action plan  
* Reference Artifacts  
  * [Kickoff Call Screenshare / Slide Deck](#koc-call-format-&-slide-deck)

# **Foundations Preferences Live Setup** {#foundations-preferences-live-setup}

The intention here is for the OBM to ask questions guiding through these areas, which the client will answer and the EA will execute. For example, the EA can edit a calendar SOP document and then modify an ideal calendar in Google calendar as the client responds, or the EA can edit labels for email categories as the client tweaks a proposed system.

Depending on time to complete, OBM/EA can guide client through only a portion (e.g. first half) of data points/preferences per area.

## **Calendar**

* Choose earliest/latest meeting times  
* Set rules on back-to-backs, hours of meetings per day, etc  
* Review ideal week suggested by AI  
* Confirm adding meeting bot to find delegations  
* Accept/reject quick wins  
  * Choose goal for number of uninterrupted focus blocks (e.g. 3 x 2h blocks per week)  
  * Choose preferred days for stacking meetings, or by types of meeting (internal vs external, 1-1‚Äôs vs team, etc)  
  * Choose periodicity for other recurring things (e.g. massage, spa, date night, friend/social events like board game night or outdoors trips, etc)  
  * Meeting bio format and on/off (e.g. VCs yes, sales leads yes, partnerships no)

###

* Review and customize [Athena default email labeling system](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1PJ5OYeta1IX5uwSnNpHdrKAeABHYncNEScMYf2Tp5_8/preview)  
  * Some Athena default system they can accept or tweak, e.g.  
    * \! Priority  
    * Response Needed  
    * Review Pre-Draft  
    * Responded  
    * Waiting On  
    * Receipts  
    * Travel

* Choose time for [EA email sweeps](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1PJ5OYeta1IX5uwSnNpHdrKAeABHYncNEScMYf2Tp5_8/preview)  
* Review suggestions for when EA should email as EA vs client  
* Review suggestions for pre-draft vs just send  
* Accept/reject quick wins  
  * Autolabel all Substack/Beehiiv/other newsletters to create a calmer inbox  
  * Policy for EA unsubscribing from marketing/sales emails, marking spam, etc  
  * Automations for receipts, vendor invoices, personal deliveries e.g. Amazon, flight confirmations, hotel/Airbnb confirmations, etc

* Review AI pre-drafted emails in client writing voice prepared by AI/EA; incorporate feedback  
  * Personal  
  * Business

**Note**: Recommend gifting over travel since quicker and relevant to infrequent travelers; abandon travel mid-way to ensure time to complete delegation skill practice and goal-setting portions of call.

## **Pre-AI/Pre-Productization Implementations**  {#pre-ai/pre-productization-implementations}

*Below are instructions for prefilling data points manually before, or in addition to, AI-driven extraction methods.*

**Finding Client Preferences/defining SOPs manually and via targeted searches**

* Calendar SOPs  
  * EAs can review the calendar manually, or take screenshots of last few weeks and send to ChatGPT to extract calendar preferences into text/SOP  
* Email SOPs  
  * Most of these are probably just Athena defaults that aren‚Äôt determined by an AI scanning the client inbox  
    * E.g. labeling system, when EA should respond as EA vs client, etc  
* Flight SOPs  
  * EAs can prefill the doc by doing structured Gmail search  
    * in:inbox category:reservations "flight" "baggage" "confirmation"  
* Hotel & Airbnb SOPs  
  * EAs can prefill the doc by doing structured Gmail search  
    * *in:inbox category:reservations "hotel" "confirmation"*   
    * *category:reservations from:\*@airbnb.com  "confirmed" \-"request sent"*   
* Gift SOPs  
  * EA can prefill the doc doing structured Gmail search, but very difficult without names of recipients; most AI-dependent SOP  
    * *("gift message" OR "gift order") AND "confirmation"*   
      * High precision, but screens some out  
    * *category:purchases "shipment" OR "shipped" OR "shipping" \-{client\_address}*  
      * Will screen out partner/children/other gifts sometimes  
    * *category:purchases "shipment" OR "shipped" OR "shipping" \-{client\_name}*  
      * Will screen out gifts where client name is given in payment email  
    * category:purchases "shipment" OR "shipped" OR "shipping"   
      * Requires manual sorting to eliminate client‚Äôs own purchases  
      * May be better to limit to Christmas period to find names  
* Key Contacts & Vendors  
  * EA can prefill the doc doing structured Gmail search  
    * Accountant  
      * *from:me ("tax return" OR "accountant" OR "CPA" OR "IRS" OR "2023 return") has:attachment*  
    * Attorney  
      * *from:me "contract" (attorney OR lawyer) has:attachment*  
    * Doctors & Medical Providers  
      * *filename:ics (visit OR appointment OR e-visit OR consultation) AND (medical OR doctor OR prescription OR clinic OR dr. OR patient OR MRN OR HIPAA OR hospital) \-flight \-hotel \-"conference room"*   
      * *("doctor visit" OR "appointment confirmation" OR "appointment details" OR "visit confirmation" OR "visit details" OR "video appointment" OR "video visit") AND (doctor OR dr. OR provider OR medical OR clinic OR "prior authorization" OR hipaa OR EHR OR orthopedic OR specialist OR therapist OR prescriptions OR "medical records" OR nurse OR NP OR ", MD" OR "current prescriptions" OR "current medications") \-flight \-hotel \-"conference room" \-unsubscribe \-"manage preferences"  \-"genius bar"  \-"CVS" \-"Walgreens"*    
    * Masseuse or Spa  
      * *appointment ("massage" OR "spa")*  
      * *in:inbox appointment ("massage" OR "spa")*   
    * Hair  
      * *in:inbox appointment ("hair" OR "haircut" OR "salon")*

**Outline**

* Client goals & playbook sequencing review  
  * Did we do what we said we were supposed to do last time?  
  * If not, why not? Can we schedule it, or tweak it?  
* Inspiring delegations   
  * Ideally filtered by relevance/tags, when able  
* Review last period‚Äôs delegations  
  * Celebrate wins \+ offer constructive feedback

* Review last period‚Äôs feedback to EA

W1 voice delegation & Loom deepdive, W2 [Dan Martell-type Exercises](#other-sources), W4 [energy audit](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1vmQmuuCsTg3ObOg0hONwGaPCMua6XO9p/view?usp=drive_link) or [zone of genius](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1vbMGx2gE6fES7fZggJwZphaB9FtqKHar/view?usp=drive_link), etc

  * What have we not attempted to delegate yet, or couldn‚Äôt figure out?  
  * If we could only delegate one thing to get the most quality of life improvement, what would it be?  
  * What [1 personal area and 1 business area](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1p3jXtOMcbnsAMJqxKrSIMZ7m2mmgK89qeRUzRJ3h5NY/edit#heading=h.pneypgke88po) should we try to delegate more?  
  * Etc

# **Scripted Proactivity Ideas** {#scripted-proactivity-ideas}

Some selection of these, or similar ideas, can be scheduled for EAs to execute for new clients on certain days of the first few months to drive value, surprise, and delight.

1. Gift spreadsheet/CRM \+ recurring tasks; email with 5 options for any gift event coming up in the next 60 days  
2. Recurring scheduling of doctor appointments, massages, haircuts, etc  
3. Spreadsheet of recurring bills \+ subscriptions, w process to review \+ cancel (business \+ personal)  
4. Recommended recurring purchase SOP, e.g. groceries, toiletries, etc based on Instacart/Amazon history or AI email scan  
5. Presentation of reading list based on company/industry  
6. Setup of automations, e.g. saving receipts to a Google Drive folder  
7. Personal upskilling plan based on client business‚Äô apps (e.g. Notion/Coda/Airtable/Pipedrive/etc) or goals  
8. Creation of ideal week template in new calendar \+ prepared questions  
9. Google alerts or social media monitoring for company  
10. AI/EA-written email examples to calibrate voice and tone  
11. Creation of renewal reminders (e.g. driver‚Äôs license, passport, visa, Global Entry, TSA Pre ‚úì, non-renewing memberships, etc)  
12. Pre-Meeting Bios  
13. Week-End Calendar Audit  
14. AI book summaries for recent Kindle/Audible purchases  
15. AI newsletter summary

# **EA Norms & Collaboration Nuances** {#ea-norms-&-collaboration-nuances}

* General preferences for speed vs perfection  
  * Do they generally value being super careful or efficiency/velocity?   
  * What is their comfort level with the EA making assumptions to get something done vs. a lot of back-and-forth around little details?   
  * Does it vary by task/area? Etc.  
* Communication  
  * How much communication do they like, and on what medium?   
    * If EA is checking the pharmacy for me every 2 days, do I want a message every time you check, or only when the pharmacy restocks, or maybe every 3 times (i.e. once per week)?  
  * Do you prefer constant status updates even with little new information, only at meaningful milestones, or only when something is done or blocked?  
* Handling Urgent / Emergent Situations  
  * For example, let's say the EA scheduled a massage at 7pm and the client is in a meeting until 6:30pm. The massage place messages the EA on WhatsApp at 6:15pm saying they need to move it an hour, or to tomorrow.   
    * Should the EA call the client as soon as the meeting is supposed to be over? Or when they predict the client will start traveling?  
    * Should they not call at all, knowing that the client is almost 100% likely to check their messages before leaving, or see a notification about the calendar event being canceled?  
    * If they know for a fact the client is free the rest of the evening, should they just accept moving it 1 hour later if they're confident that's what the client would do?   
  * Does the client prefer this type of autonomy/efficiency over the potential back-and-forth?  
* Prioritizing Tasks  
  * How should the EA prioritize tasks, or imply due dates if they aren't specified?   
  * Should they just check with you when they aren‚Äôt sure, or make their best guess and start working?  
  * What rules of thumb could they use?  
* Unblocking EA  
  * If you delegate something but it isn't clear or requires more information to execute, would they rather the EA wait until they're able to respond, or try to get the info via some other means?   
    * For example, you could get my brother's address from texting my mom, if for some reason it isn't in my inbox or you know the address has changed.   
    * Similarly, if I ask you to research something work related but don't provide enough detail, would I rather you send me a bunch of questions, or email someone else in the company?   
      * Some clients don't want the EA emailing their VP of marketing to unblock a task, and some do.   
* How forceful/aggressive do they want the EA to be?   
  * If the client keeps procrastinating their part of a task that needs to be unblocked, how should they handle it?   
  * Is it different if it's something with a real risk, like missing info for a tax return or missing someone's birthday, vs something the client has committed to themselves, such as making a go/no-go decision on hiring a contractor or executive coach or whatever?  
  * If you are delegating unclearly or doing things that impact your EA‚Äôs ability to help you, how open are you to feedback?   
    * How often, how quickly, and how directly do you like it?  
* How should the EA manage tasks you need to do?  
  * Does the client like the EA assigning tasks to them in the task manager, or staying on top of them in some other way, like via DM?   
    * E.g. should you create a task for me to pick up the prescription, once you confirm the pharmacy has it, or just send me a Slack message?  
    * Should you send a Slack message every day until I pick it up? Every 3 days?  
* Navigating Tradeoffs  
  * Time and People  
    * For example, is it okay to move a meeting with person X or activity Y for person A or activity B?   
    * Do they have to check with you first, or should the EA just do it?  
  * Purchases & Costs  
    * The EA researched gifts for someone, and sent the client 5 options, all around $100. The client picks one, but it sold out during the back-and-forth.   
    * Should the EA just buy one of the other options, or wait to re-confirm?  
    * What if the same gift is available, but actually it was on a flash sale. The price is now $250. Should the EA just buy it, or double-check first?  
    * What if it's on Friday, and waiting until Monday would mean the gift won't arrive on time? Does that change the answer?  
  * What are the general rules you use yourself to make tradeoffs?  
  * Notes  
    * Some of these will be captured in SOPs like travel tradeoffs, but the calendar SOP probably wouldn't say "are we allowed to cancel my biweekly massage for the VC meeting?" And it might even depend on which VC. They may not have been fundraising when they onboarded, but are 6 months later, so I think the best way to handle this is sort of high level goals/priorities since a playbook for a calendar might not be specific enough.  
* Developing & Managing Proactivity  
  * If the EA is doing something that the client didn't ask for, either because they identified it proactively, it was obviously something they should do (e.g. fell under an email SOP), or is a related/derivative/implied task to one the client assigned like following-up on an invoice, should they both message it and add it to the task manager?   
    * Should they do one but not the other?   
    * Is it the same for every type of task?   
  * What about suggesting things they ***could*** do for the client which the client hasn't asked?   
    * Some people actually like when their EA scolds them for doing something the client said they shouldn't do, or if the client does something they said they wanted to delegate.  
* Definition of Done  
  * When is a task "done"?   
  * If I assign a task like "research headphones to buy", do you mark it complete when the client signals they are happy with the research, or only after the EA confirms they've received the headphones?   
    * Is this two tasks, or one task?   
  * If a task involves updates, like some kind of back-and-forth with procurement before an invoice can be paid, how often or under what circumstances does the client want to be updated?   
    * Is it if the task takes longer than X time period, only if something seems potentially going wrong, every X days until it's done, every time some significant information is provided, etc?  
* Playbooks & Standardization  
  * What is the threshold for turning something from a task to an SOP/playbook?   
  * If the EA thinks it will be done repeatedly from the description, if they have done it at least twice before, if they have an idea to automate it even if it's not a regular schedule but more rules-based, etc?   
    * Is it based on a certain time savings? Something else?  
  * How much do they like the EA making criticisms of their processes, or suggesting alternative ways to do things?   
    * Do you want the EA's to "push" playbooks to you?   
      * I.e. maybe not criticizing how they do things, but saying "you said you want to improve how you manage X, here is how another client/EA team have approached it." Or a podcast of someone's system for doing it.   
* Upskilling & Talent Development  
  * What skills are they hoping the EA is able to develop?   
    * How much are you willing to invest in your EA‚Äôs upskilling?   
      * For example, are they comfortable with the EA buying a $50 course on automation or AI or no code, but not a $500 one? Does one require asking and not the other?   
      * Should the EA only ask if they've tried a lot of free content first?   
      * Would they prefer the EA not buy courses, and instead hire a skilled contractor to teach them how to do it or create Loom videos/guides?  
* Uses of Downtime & Underutilization  
  * What are the best uses of down time?   
    * Research tasks  
    * Upskilling  
    * Long-term but low priority projects (e.g. personal CRM, travel plans, file organization)
